1
00:01:43,240 --> 00:01:45,070
Morning, Mr. Thrombey.

2
00:01:58,800 --> 00:02:00,670
Mr. Thrombey? You up there?

3
00:02:01,720 --> 00:02:03,350
Mr. Thrombey, I'm coming in.

4
00:02:14,640 --> 00:02:15,670
Shit!

5
00:02:36,880 --> 00:02:38,950
<i>You killed him, you bastard!</i>

6
00:02:39,040 --> 00:02:40,190
<i>You murdered him!</i>

7
00:02:40,280 --> 00:02:41,630
<i>I didn't murder nobody!</i>

8
00:02:41,720 --> 00:02:43,120
<i>You slashed his face open.</i>

9
00:02:43,200 --> 00:02:45,590
<i>You left him bleeding in the street
like a stuck pig,</i>

10
00:02:45,680 --> 00:02:47,630
<i>then you crushed his skull with a forklift</i>

11
00:02:47,720 --> 00:02:50,110
<i>and burned his hands off
to erase the fingerprints!</i>

12
00:02:50,200 --> 00:02:51,550
<i>You'll never prove it.</i>

13
00:02:51,640 --> 00:02:53,710
<i>We have the nanny-cam footage!</i>

14
00:02:53,800 --> 00:02:55,510
Alice, turn that off now, please?

15
00:02:55,600 --> 00:02:57,810
- Why? It's almost over.
- Now. Please, just turn it off.

16
00:02:57,840 --> 00:03:00,210
They're finding out who did it
and the Wi-Fi sucks in my room...

17
00:03:00,240 --> 00:03:02,330
- Turn it off, now. Alice!
- There's two minutes left.

18
00:03:02,360 --> 00:03:04,240
- What? There isn't even anything bad on.
- Off!

19
00:03:04,280 --> 00:03:05,930
It's just normal TV,
and they're just talking!

20
00:03:05,960 --> 00:03:07,310
They're talking murder on it!

21
00:03:07,400 --> 00:03:09,960
- They're just talking.
- Your sister just had a friend she loved

22
00:03:10,000 --> 00:03:13,230
slit his throat open and she doesn't need
to be hearing that right now!

23
00:03:13,320 --> 00:03:14,640
Let's be sensitive!

24
00:03:19,000 --> 00:03:20,960
Alice, you can keep watching your show.
It's fine.

25
00:03:21,040 --> 00:03:23,150
- No, I guessed who did it anyway.
- It's okay.

26
00:03:23,240 --> 00:03:24,270
I'm sorry, Marta.

27
00:03:24,360 --> 00:03:25,630
It's okay.

28
00:03:27,600 --> 00:03:28,600
It's Harlan's son.

29
00:03:32,560 --> 00:03:33,590
Hi, Walt.

30
00:03:33,680 --> 00:03:34,950
<i>Hi, Marta, it's Walt.</i>

31
00:03:35,760 --> 00:03:37,710
<i>Would you mind coming to the house early?</i>

32
00:03:37,800 --> 00:03:40,440
<i>The police have
a few more questions for everybody.</i>

33
00:03:41,000 --> 00:03:42,070
What?

34
00:04:01,880 --> 00:04:03,790
Hey. Excuse me, ma'am.

35
00:04:03,880 --> 00:04:05,070
You with the help?

36
00:04:05,160 --> 00:04:07,830
Hey! Her name's Marta.
She was Granddad's nurse.

37
00:04:07,920 --> 00:04:10,150
She's with us. "The help"?

38
00:04:10,840 --> 00:04:12,670
It's okay. I'm sorry.

39
00:04:12,760 --> 00:04:15,110
No, it's not okay. What the hell?

40
00:04:24,880 --> 00:04:26,030
How are you doing?

41
00:04:28,040 --> 00:04:29,390
Not very good.

42
00:04:29,480 --> 00:04:30,480
Alone.

43
00:04:31,600 --> 00:04:35,070
Lots of this
and not knowing what to do next.

44
00:04:36,080 --> 00:04:39,190
Marta, anything you need...

45
00:04:39,880 --> 00:04:41,390
You're part of this family.

46
00:04:43,360 --> 00:04:44,580
Thank you.

47
00:04:46,280 --> 00:04:48,270
- How you doing, kiddo?
- Linda.

48
00:04:49,360 --> 00:04:50,630
How are you?

49
00:04:52,640 --> 00:04:56,030
You know, the funeral helped, I guess.
Just seeing him.

50
00:04:56,360 --> 00:04:57,910
I thought you should have been there.

51
00:04:58,000 --> 00:04:59,870
- I was outvoted.
- Get arrested!

52
00:04:59,960 --> 00:05:02,270
- Die up your own ass for all I care!
- Richard.

53
00:05:03,560 --> 00:05:04,670
He's not coming.

54
00:05:05,880 --> 00:05:07,550
Ransom. Little shit.

55
00:05:07,640 --> 00:05:08,640
Missed the funeral.

56
00:05:09,320 --> 00:05:10,750
Excuse me.

57
00:05:10,840 --> 00:05:13,990
We're ready for you now.
We'd like to see you one at a time.

58
00:05:14,080 --> 00:05:16,270
All right. I'll go first.

59
00:05:16,360 --> 00:05:19,990
I'm assuming this will all be wrapped up
before the memorial tonight.

60
00:05:20,440 --> 00:05:21,660
We'll do our best, ma'am.

61
00:05:24,520 --> 00:05:25,550
So...

62
00:05:26,040 --> 00:05:27,310
how you doing, kiddo?

63
00:05:28,800 --> 00:05:31,360
We're just gonna reintroduce ourselves
as a formality.

64
00:05:31,440 --> 00:05:33,070
I am Detective Lieutenant Elliott,

65
00:05:33,160 --> 00:05:35,030
and this is Trooper Wagner.

66
00:05:35,120 --> 00:05:40,430
Now, I'm going to record this,
just to make things easier.

67
00:05:40,520 --> 00:05:43,750
All right, we're with
Linda Drysdale nÃ©e Thrombey,

68
00:05:43,840 --> 00:05:45,590
Harlan Thrombey's eldest daughter,

69
00:05:45,680 --> 00:05:49,270
and discussing the events that took place
the night of his demise one week ago.

70
00:05:49,360 --> 00:05:50,710
November 8th.

71
00:05:50,800 --> 00:05:52,510
We're very sorry for your loss.

72
00:05:54,080 --> 00:05:56,230
Thank you. That means a lot.

73
00:05:56,800 --> 00:05:59,950
So, we understand on that night
the family had gathered

74
00:06:00,040 --> 00:06:02,680
- to celebrate your father's 85th birthday?
- Yes.

75
00:06:03,400 --> 00:06:05,550
- How was it?
- The party?

76
00:06:06,200 --> 00:06:07,520
Pre-my-dad's-death?

77
00:06:08,200 --> 00:06:09,710
Oh, it was great.

78
00:06:10,160 --> 00:06:12,350
Did anyone besides the family show face?

79
00:06:13,320 --> 00:06:15,030
<i>Fran, the housekeeper.</i>

80
00:06:15,120 --> 00:06:18,230
He was a nice guy, but he was so hairy.

81
00:06:18,320 --> 00:06:20,070
- Jacob?
- And I've dated Italian guys.

82
00:06:20,160 --> 00:06:21,910
You know what I mean? It was like...

83
00:06:22,000 --> 00:06:24,590
<i>Marta, Harlan's caregiver.</i>

84
00:06:24,680 --> 00:06:26,590
<i>Good girl. Hard worker.</i>

85
00:06:26,680 --> 00:06:28,230
Her family's from Ecuador.

86
00:06:29,040 --> 00:06:30,190
And Wanetta.

87
00:06:30,800 --> 00:06:32,910
<i>Greatnana. Harlan's mom.</i>

88
00:06:33,000 --> 00:06:34,830
- Hi, Nana.
<i>- His mom?</i>

89
00:06:35,440 --> 00:06:37,310
- Nana?
<i>- Wow. How old is she?</i>

90
00:06:38,040 --> 00:06:39,110
<i>We have no idea.</i>

91
00:06:39,640 --> 00:06:41,310
Okay... and your son, Ransom,

92
00:06:42,160 --> 00:06:43,310
<i>did he attend as well?</i>

93
00:06:43,400 --> 00:06:45,030
<i>Yes, but he left early.</i>

94
00:06:45,920 --> 00:06:49,190
Ransom, are you leaving?

95
00:06:54,320 --> 00:06:55,320
Right.

96
00:06:55,400 --> 00:06:58,190
Would you say that all three of you
showed up around the same time?

97
00:06:59,320 --> 00:07:00,720
No.

98
00:07:03,040 --> 00:07:06,630
Richard came early
to help the caterers set up.

99
00:07:06,720 --> 00:07:09,950
Okay. And you and your husband, Richard,
work at a real estate firm in Boston?

100
00:07:10,040 --> 00:07:12,500
No. It's... It's my company.

101
00:07:12,600 --> 00:07:14,110
Right. Right. Sorry.

102
00:07:14,200 --> 00:07:15,760
I built my business from the ground up.

103
00:07:15,800 --> 00:07:17,150
Oh, just like your father.

104
00:07:17,840 --> 00:07:19,110
You two were very close.

105
00:07:20,440 --> 00:07:23,790
We... We had our own secret way
of communicating.

106
00:07:23,920 --> 00:07:27,030
I mean, you had to find that... with Dad.

107
00:07:27,120 --> 00:07:29,070
You had to find a game to play with him,

108
00:07:29,160 --> 00:07:32,670
and if you did that,
and you played by his rules...

109
00:07:38,520 --> 00:07:40,750
Everyone idolizes their dad, right?

110
00:07:41,240 --> 00:07:42,830
I don't know. Do they?

111
00:07:44,000 --> 00:07:45,150
Very much not.

112
00:07:45,960 --> 00:07:47,180
Don't know why I said that.

113
00:07:48,040 --> 00:07:49,440
<i>But my wife, Linda, does.</i>

114
00:07:50,120 --> 00:07:52,430
<i>Harlan started out
with a rusty Smith Corona</i>

115
00:07:52,520 --> 00:07:56,710
<i>and built himself into one of the
best-selling mystery writers of all time.</i>

116
00:07:56,800 --> 00:08:00,990
Wow, seems like all his kids
are self-made overachievers.

117
00:08:03,240 --> 00:08:04,430
Sure.

118
00:08:04,520 --> 00:08:06,630
For the record,
I'm speaking with Walt Thrombey,

119
00:08:06,720 --> 00:08:09,110
Harlan Thrombey's youngest son.

120
00:08:09,200 --> 00:08:11,760
So you run your father's
publishing company?

121
00:08:11,840 --> 00:08:14,150
Yeah. It's my... It's our...

122
00:08:14,240 --> 00:08:16,230
It's the family's publishing company.

123
00:08:16,320 --> 00:08:17,590
Dad trusts me to run it.

124
00:08:18,840 --> 00:08:20,320
Thirty languages.

125
00:08:20,400 --> 00:08:23,830
Over 80 million copies sold.
A real legacy.

126
00:08:24,920 --> 00:08:25,920
You guys fans?

127
00:08:26,000 --> 00:08:28,670
I mean, I don't do much
fiction reading myself, but...

128
00:08:28,760 --> 00:08:30,270
Big fan. I'm a big fan.

129
00:08:30,360 --> 00:08:32,510
I mean, his plots are just like...

130
00:08:32,600 --> 00:08:35,470
Like, I won't spoil it for you but...
Okay, like <i>Thousand Knives?</i>

131
00:08:35,560 --> 00:08:36,880
The cow and the shotgun.

132
00:08:36,960 --> 00:08:39,190
Like, where do you come up with that?

133
00:08:39,280 --> 00:08:42,870
Well, Dad said the plots just popped
into his head, fully formed.

134
00:08:43,000 --> 00:08:44,430
It was the easy part for him.

135
00:08:47,240 --> 00:08:48,460
So you're in the area, right?

136
00:08:48,560 --> 00:08:51,120
So, you guys probably arrived
around the same time.

137
00:08:53,160 --> 00:08:55,150
We all got here around 8:00.

138
00:08:55,240 --> 00:08:57,830
<i>My wife, Donna, she's my rock.</i>

139
00:08:59,640 --> 00:09:01,670
Jesus, Donna! Are you all right?

140
00:09:02,320 --> 00:09:05,150
<i>My son, Jacob, he's 16.</i>

141
00:09:05,240 --> 00:09:07,670
<i>Very politically active.</i>

142
00:09:07,760 --> 00:09:09,190
The boy is literally a Nazi.

143
00:09:09,280 --> 00:09:11,030
He's an alt-right troll dipshit.

144
00:09:11,760 --> 00:09:13,950
Kids today with the Internet,
it's amazing.

145
00:09:15,240 --> 00:09:16,510
So the night went well?

146
00:09:18,760 --> 00:09:20,630
<i>I mean, we're all gutted, but...</i>

147
00:09:20,720 --> 00:09:22,910
<i>I was happy to have that night with him.</i>

148
00:09:23,040 --> 00:09:24,230
<i>To be by his side,</i>

149
00:09:24,320 --> 00:09:27,670
<i>to think about our books
and what we've accomplished with them.</i>

150
00:09:28,280 --> 00:09:30,920
It's like I can still feel his hand
on my shoulder.

151
00:09:32,400 --> 00:09:33,750
Passing the torch.

152
00:09:34,280 --> 00:09:36,470
So, we're here with Joni Thrombey,

153
00:09:36,560 --> 00:09:38,390
Harlan Thrombey's daughter-in-law?

154
00:09:39,320 --> 00:09:41,270
Yeah, I married his son, Neil.

155
00:09:41,360 --> 00:09:43,390
We had one daughter, Meg.

156
00:09:43,520 --> 00:09:47,350
And then Neil passed on 15 years ago.

157
00:09:47,480 --> 00:09:49,470
But you remained close to the Thrombeys?

158
00:09:50,520 --> 00:09:52,070
They're my family.

159
00:09:55,040 --> 00:09:57,550
<i>I feel simultaneously freed by</i>

160
00:09:58,280 --> 00:10:01,270
<i>and supported by them.</i>

161
00:10:04,960 --> 00:10:08,190
It's that balance of opposites
that's the nugget of Flam.

162
00:10:09,120 --> 00:10:10,390
Sorry, the nugget of...

163
00:10:10,480 --> 00:10:11,910
Flam.

164
00:10:12,000 --> 00:10:14,790
Oh, yeah, Flam,
your skin care company. Sorry.

165
00:10:14,880 --> 00:10:16,360
I forgive you.

166
00:10:17,080 --> 00:10:20,390
Yeah, it's skin care,
but it promotes a total lifestyle.

167
00:10:20,480 --> 00:10:24,030
Self-sufficiency with an acknowledgement
of human need.

168
00:10:24,120 --> 00:10:25,230
That's Flam.

169
00:10:25,320 --> 00:10:26,830
But it's also Harlan.

170
00:10:27,240 --> 00:10:29,430
He got me and Meg
through some tough times.

171
00:10:29,720 --> 00:10:31,670
Granddad gives my mom a yearly allowance

172
00:10:31,760 --> 00:10:34,910
and he's never missed wiring
a tuition payment to my schools.

173
00:10:37,080 --> 00:10:39,310
He's a genuinely selfless man.

174
00:10:39,840 --> 00:10:41,830
But you left the party early?

175
00:10:41,920 --> 00:10:42,950
Have fun.

176
00:10:43,040 --> 00:10:44,230
<i>To see some friends at Smith.</i>

177
00:10:44,320 --> 00:10:49,990
You know Dad pays for her
crypto-Marxist-post-deconstructural-

178
00:10:50,080 --> 00:10:52,590
feminist-poetry-theory-whatever major?

179
00:10:53,200 --> 00:10:54,950
She could have stuck around for the cake.

180
00:10:55,560 --> 00:10:57,310
<i>I think Linda was upset.</i>

181
00:11:01,200 --> 00:11:02,680
But Harlan understood.

182
00:11:07,120 --> 00:11:08,120
Right.

183
00:11:08,840 --> 00:11:11,790
You two showed up to the party
around the same time...

184
00:11:11,880 --> 00:11:13,990
If I could pause?

185
00:11:14,080 --> 00:11:15,230
Because I just...

186
00:11:15,960 --> 00:11:17,150
Who is that guy?

187
00:11:17,280 --> 00:11:20,480
- And why are we doing all this again?
- These are just some follow-up questions.

188
00:11:20,560 --> 00:11:23,630
We're attempting to be thorough,
so we can figure out the manner of death.

189
00:11:24,240 --> 00:11:26,800
So by "manner of death,"
you mean if someone killed him?

190
00:11:26,880 --> 00:11:28,790
If one of us killed him?

191
00:11:28,880 --> 00:11:31,170
- One of his family killed him?
- No, Walt... Walt, no, no.

192
00:11:31,200 --> 00:11:33,070
Is that what you're suggesting,
Lieutenant?

193
00:11:33,160 --> 00:11:35,310
No one's saying that, okay?
This is all pro forma.

194
00:11:36,080 --> 00:11:37,080
Okay.

195
00:11:37,960 --> 00:11:39,630
So who the fuck is that?

196
00:11:41,640 --> 00:11:43,150
This is Benoit Blanc.

197
00:11:43,960 --> 00:11:46,030
- Benoit Blanc?
- Yes.

198
00:11:46,720 --> 00:11:49,510
Mr. Blanc is a private investigator
of great renown.

199
00:11:49,600 --> 00:11:50,600
Wait a minute.

200
00:11:51,120 --> 00:11:54,030
I read a tweet about
a <i>New Yorker</i> article about you.

201
00:11:54,120 --> 00:11:56,510
"The Last of the Gentlemen Sleuths."

202
00:11:56,600 --> 00:11:58,870
You solved that case
with the tennis champ.

203
00:12:00,080 --> 00:12:01,990
You're famous.

204
00:12:02,080 --> 00:12:04,230
Mr. Blanc is not
with the police department

205
00:12:04,320 --> 00:12:05,950
and not officially involved in the case,

206
00:12:06,040 --> 00:12:07,630
but he's offered to consult.

207
00:12:07,720 --> 00:12:10,230
Now I happily obliged,
and I can vouch for him.

208
00:12:10,320 --> 00:12:11,950
Mr. Blanc, I know who you are.

209
00:12:12,040 --> 00:12:13,830
I read your profile in the <i>New Yorker.</i>

210
00:12:13,960 --> 00:12:15,670
I found it delightful.

211
00:12:16,320 --> 00:12:20,950
I just buried my 85-year-old father
who committed suicide.

212
00:12:21,480 --> 00:12:22,830
Why are you here?

213
00:12:24,600 --> 00:12:27,510
I'm here at the behest of a client.

214
00:12:28,200 --> 00:12:29,200
Who?

215
00:12:30,640 --> 00:12:32,470
I cannot say.

216
00:12:32,560 --> 00:12:33,990
But let me assure you of this.

217
00:12:34,600 --> 00:12:37,550
My presence will be ornamental.

218
00:12:38,080 --> 00:12:40,720
You will find me a respectful,

219
00:12:40,800 --> 00:12:43,630
quiet, passive observer...

220
00:12:44,720 --> 00:12:45,940
of the truth.

221
00:12:47,000 --> 00:12:48,000
Fine.

222
00:12:49,120 --> 00:12:50,390
Are we getting there?

223
00:12:50,480 --> 00:12:51,670
Nearly. Um...

224
00:12:51,760 --> 00:12:55,640
Harlan's nurse, she was at the party
in a professional capacity?

225
00:12:56,000 --> 00:12:57,030
Marta?

226
00:12:57,680 --> 00:12:58,680
I guess.

227
00:12:59,360 --> 00:13:03,270
<i>Harlan hired her to be around to take care
of whatever medical needs popped up.</i>

228
00:13:03,360 --> 00:13:06,510
<i>But really, she's like part of the family.</i>

229
00:13:07,040 --> 00:13:08,260
<i>Good kid.</i>

230
00:13:08,360 --> 00:13:09,760
<i>Been a good friend to Harlan.</i>

231
00:13:10,160 --> 00:13:11,950
<i>Family's from Paraguay.</i>

232
00:13:12,040 --> 00:13:14,110
Linda really likes her work ethic.

233
00:13:15,600 --> 00:13:18,190
"Immigrants. We get the job done."

234
00:13:21,480 --> 00:13:22,750
- I...
- From <i>Hamilton.</i>

235
00:13:22,840 --> 00:13:24,320
Oh, <i>Hamilton.</i>

236
00:13:24,400 --> 00:13:25,430
It's so good.

237
00:13:25,520 --> 00:13:27,190
- I saw it at The Public.
- Oh!

238
00:13:28,840 --> 00:13:30,350
May I just...

239
00:13:31,600 --> 00:13:33,110
Then I'll recede, but...

240
00:13:33,840 --> 00:13:35,870
as a self-made man myself,

241
00:13:37,080 --> 00:13:39,070
I have to express my admiration

242
00:13:39,160 --> 00:13:41,550
for how you followed
in your father's footsteps.

243
00:13:43,440 --> 00:13:45,830
- Thank you.
- Just marvelous.

244
00:13:45,920 --> 00:13:47,870
You know, the whole family too.

245
00:13:47,960 --> 00:13:49,830
And Joni with her thing,

246
00:13:49,920 --> 00:13:52,310
and Walt with his publishing empire...

247
00:13:52,400 --> 00:13:53,620
It's...

248
00:13:54,600 --> 00:13:55,600
Well...

249
00:13:57,040 --> 00:13:59,830
Yes, I mean, Walt, he's done well

250
00:13:59,920 --> 00:14:02,070
with what Dad gave him.

251
00:14:02,160 --> 00:14:03,590
Not that it matters.

252
00:14:03,680 --> 00:14:07,750
But really, Dad hands him a book
twice a year and Walt publishes it.

